recalls.Summary: BMW of North Americal, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2023 8 Series Coupe (840i, 840i xDrive, M850i xDrive, M8), 8 Series Convertible (840i, 840i xDrive, M850i xDrive, M8), 8 Series Gran Coupe (840i, 840i xDrive, M850i xDrive, M8, Alpine B8 xDrive), 2 Series Coupe (230i, 230i xDrive, M240i xDrive, M2), and 2022-2023 Z4 sDrive30i, Z4 M40i vehicles.  When the digital key is removed from the vehicle, the Electronic Control Unit (ECU) software may still allow the power windows and sunroof to be closed.  As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard number 118, "Power-operated Window Systems."
recalls.Consequence: Unintentionally closing the windows or sunroof without the key present can increase the risk of injury to occupants inside the vehicle.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will update the software for the Electronic Control Unit (ECU), free of charge.  In addition, the digital key function via cellular service and Wi-Fi capability will be deactivated until the vehicle is updated with new software.  Owner notification letters are expected to be mailed April 11, 2023.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

issues.title: Transmission Overheating and Limp Mode
issues.description: Multiple owners report transmission overheating during spirited driving or track use, causing the vehicle to enter limp mode with reduced power and delayed shifting. The 8-speed ZF automatic transmission appears to struggle with heat management under aggressive driving conditions.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, transmission fluid change, or transmission cooler installation. Severe cases may require transmission rebuild or replacement.
issues.prevention: Avoid extended aggressive driving sessions, allow cooling periods during track use, ensure proper transmission fluid maintenance

issues.title: High-Pressure Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: The high-pressure fuel pump in the S58 engine has shown premature failure, leading to fuel starvation, rough running, and potential engine damage. This is a known issue across BMW's S58 engine family.
issues.fix_description: Replace high-pressure fuel pump and associated components. BMW may cover under warranty or extended coverage programs.
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, avoid running on very low fuel levels, follow BMW's maintenance schedule

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Roof Panel Separation
issues.description: Some owners report separation or delamination of the carbon fiber roof panel, particularly around the edges. This appears to be related to adhesive failure or manufacturing defects in early production vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Roof panel replacement or re-adhesion by BMW service center. Usually covered under warranty.
issues.prevention: Avoid parking in extreme temperatures, regular inspection of roof panel integrity

issues.title: Infotainment System Crashes and Freezes
issues.description: The iDrive 8 system experiences frequent crashes, freezes, and slow response times. Issues include black screens, unresponsive touch controls, and connectivity problems with smartphones.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, system reset, or in severe cases, infotainment unit replacement
issues.prevention: Keep software updated, avoid overloading system with multiple simultaneous functions

issues.title: Charge Pipe Failure
issues.description: The plastic charge pipes in the turbo system are prone to cracking or complete failure, especially under high boost conditions. This leads to significant power loss and potential engine damage if debris enters the intake.
issues.fix_description: Replace with upgraded aluminum charge pipes or OEM plastic parts. Many owners upgrade to aftermarket solutions.
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive tuning without supporting modifications, regular inspection of charge pipes

issues.title: Brake Pedal Feel Issues
issues.description: Multiple owners report inconsistent brake pedal feel, including spongy pedal, excessive travel, or varying bite point. This may be related to brake booster or master cylinder issues.
issues.fix_description: Brake fluid flush, brake system bleeding, or replacement of brake booster/master cylinder components
issues.prevention: Regular brake fluid changes, avoid aggressive braking that overheats the system

issues.title: Excessive Oil Consumption
issues.description: The S58 engine shows higher than normal oil consumption, with some owners needing to add oil between service intervals. This appears to be within BMW's specifications but concerning for many owners.
symptoms: Need to add oil between services
issues.fix_description: Monitor oil levels regularly, potential warranty claim if consumption exceeds BMW limits. May require engine work in extreme cases.
issues.prevention: Use BMW approved oil, regular oil level checks, avoid extended high-RPM operation when engine is cold

issues.title: Adaptive LED Headlight Malfunction
issues.description: The adaptive LED headlight system experiences various failures including individual LED segments going out, adaptive functions not working properly, and complete headlight unit failures.
issues.fix_description: LED module replacement or complete headlight unit replacement. Often covered under warranty.
issues.prevention: Avoid high-pressure washing directly on headlights, regular inspection for moisture ingress

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: Electronic door handles occasionally fail to extend or retract properly, leaving occupants unable to exit the vehicle easily. This appears to be related to actuator motor failures.
issues.fix_description: Replace door handle actuator mechanism or complete handle assembly
issues.prevention: Keep door handle area clean, avoid excessive force when operating handles

issues.title: Cooling System Leaks
issues.description: Various cooling system components including water pumps, thermostats, and coolant hoses have shown premature failure, leading to coolant leaks and potential overheating.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty cooling components, flush cooling system, pressure test for additional leaks
issues.prevention: Regular cooling system inspections, use only BMW approved coolant, avoid overheating

editorial.tagline: Pure M Division fury in compact perfection
editorial.hero_blurb: The G87 M2 delivers uncompromising M performance in BMW's most focused package. With the legendary S58 twin-turbo straight-six and rear-wheel drive precision, it's the purest M car money can buy.
editorial.essence: The M2 G87 represents BMW M's commitment to driver-focused engineering without compromise. It combines the brutal power of the S58 engine with a compact chassis that prioritizes engagement over comfort, creating an authentic M experience that cuts through modern automotive bloat.
editorial.heritage: Born from the legendary 2002 Turbo and evolved through the 1M Coupe lineage, the M2 carries forward BMW's tradition of compact performance machines. The G87 generation marks the fourth iteration, refined through decades of M Division expertise.
editorial.design_philosophy: Designers prioritized function over form, creating aggressive proportions with massive air intakes, flared fenders, and purposeful aerodynamics. Every line serves performance, from the carbon fiber roof to the quad exhaust tips.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a direct racing derivative, the M2 shares DNA with BMW's touring car programs and serves as the foundation for customer racing vehicles in various series worldwide.
editorial.engine_character: The S58 delivers relentless, linear power with explosive mid-range torque that pins you to the seat. It's smooth yet savage, building intensity from 2,500 RPM to a screaming 7,200 RPM redline with unwavering determination.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 8-speed ZF automatic snaps through gears with surgical precision, while the 6-speed manual offers mechanical satisfaction with perfectly weighted throws and a satisfying clutch pedal engagement.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The chassis is taut and responsive, with adaptive dampers that balance track capability with street usability. It's playful at the limit, rewarding skilled drivers with controllable oversteer and predictable breakaway characteristics.
editorial.steering_feel: The steering delivers pure communication through the wheel, with proper weight and feedback that builds confidence through corners. It's precise without being nervous, perfectly calibrated for both canyon carving and track work.
editorial.brake_confidence: M compound brakes provide fade-resistant stopping power with excellent pedal feel. They inspire confidence on track while remaining civilized for street driving, with strong initial bite and progressive modulation.
editorial.sound_signature: The S58 produces a distinctive growl that builds to an aggressive roar under acceleration, punctuated by pops and crackles on overrun. It's authentically mechanical without being artificially enhanced.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who prioritize engagement over comfort, track day enthusiasts, and BMW loyalists who want unfiltered M performance in a focused package.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Comfort-seekers, those needing rear seat space, luxury-focused buyers, or drivers who prefer understated styling.
editorial.buyers_summary: The G87 M2 is BMW M Division's most honest offering, prioritizing driver connection over convenience. Choose manual for maximum engagement or automatic for track performance, but either way expect an uncompromising machine that demands your attention.

expertReviews.title: 2025 BMW M2 manual review. Is the M2 one of the last true driver's cars on sale today?
pros: Rear-drive manual transmission with straight-six engine - rare combination in 2025
Excellent dynamics and handling that's easy to read and hugely enjoyable
Practical with large boot space and usable daily driving capability
Distinctive muscular looks that say 'I'm a naughty sort of car'
Strong performance with proper muscle from low RPM thanks to twin turbos
Good manual gearbox with nice rev-matching blips
Traction control MS setting provides freedom without going completely off
cons: Expensive at £75,000 as tested with many options being extra cost
Heavy at 1,700kg - 200kg heavier than E46 M3
Steering wheel too fat and doesn't feel connected like other sports cars
Track carbon seats create awkward clutch pedal position causing leg ache
Cheap plastic materials in some areas despite high price
Clutch positioned oddly in center rather than left of steering wheel
expertReviews.verdict: The M2 represents one of the last true driver's cars with its rare combination of rear-drive, manual transmission, and straight-six engine. While heavy and expensive, it delivers excellent dynamics and practicality. The reviewer appreciates BMW continuing to offer this configuration but notes issues with seat/pedal positioning and value. Overall seen as a proper pocket rocket that doesn't need tweaking straight from the factory.

expertReviews.title: New BMW M2 CS: The Perfect M Car? | 4K
pros: 523 bhp with 479 lb-ft torque from tuned 3.0L twin-turbo straight-6
Excellent automatic transmission with sharp paddle shifts
Brilliant sports car package with chuckable handling
More compact feel than M4
Strong braking performance with optional carbon ceramic brakes
Rear seats and practical boot space for daily use
Good exhaust sound
cons: Very expensive at almost £87,000
Weight saving measures only reduce 30kg despite carbon roof and boot
Thick steering wheel
Annoying armrest delete
Carbon ceramic brakes cost extra £8,800
Open front grills risk radiator damage
Confusing brake comfort/sport settings
expertReviews.verdict: The M2 CS is a brilliant sports car that delivers excellent performance and handling in an increasingly rare compact sports car package. While expensive and with some questionable design choices, it succeeds as a well-rounded daily driver that's also track-capable. The automatic transmission works better than the manual, and despite the high price, it offers a compelling alternative in a shrinking market of sub-100k sports cars.

expertReviews.title: 2025 BMW M2 FULL Review /// The PUREST M Car?
pros: Retains core BMW DNA with rear-wheel drive and twin-turbo inline-6
Power increased to 473 horsepower for 2025
Excellent braking system with adjustable settings and strong confidence
Carbon fiber roof lowers center of gravity
Good trunk space and practicality for daily use
New color options including Voodoo Blue paint
Lighter weight compared to other BMW models at around 3800-3900 lbs
Alcantara steering wheel feels premium and is heated
Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires appropriate for daily driving
cons: Suspension is very stiff even in comfort mode
No spare tire
Fixed bucket seats make entry more difficult
Starting at $68,000 but test vehicle was $84,000 with options
No power tailgate
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 BMW M2 receives minor updates including new interior elements, color options, and a small power bump to 473 hp. The reviewer appreciates its pure rear-wheel drive character, excellent braking system, and daily usability despite the very stiff suspension. While not a full refresh, the M2 maintains its appeal as a focused sports car that's still practical enough for daily driving.

expertReviews.title: BMW M2 (G87) | REVIEW - The Last True M Car?
pros: S58 engine is a powerhouse with 460hp and excellent power delivery
ZF 8-speed automatic is incredibly fast and smooth
Exceptional traction and handling with wide track and active differential
Excellent braking performance with 6-piston front calipers
Great value proposition at under £69,000 for performance level
Comfortable daily driver with well-built interior
Strong road presence with bold styling that grows on you
cons: Electronically assisted steering lacks feel and feedback
Brake-by-wire system feels odd at times
Exhaust valves only open in Sport/Sport+ modes
Some artificial sound enhancement through speakers
Bold styling polarizes opinions initially
Can break traction easily in wet conditions
expertReviews.verdict: The G87 M2 represents potentially the last purely petrol-powered, rear-wheel-drive M car before electrification. With the mighty S58 engine, exceptional ZF8 gearbox, and incredible chassis dynamics, it delivers an exhilarating driving experience. Despite some drawbacks like steering feel and brake-by-wire, it's an outstanding daily driver that comes alive when pushed. At under £69,000, it offers exceptional value for this level of performance and engineering.

expertReviews.title: Is the BMW G87 Still Worth It in 2025? A Two-Year Review
pros: Great value for 450+ horsepower manual RWD sports car
Excellent reliability with minimal maintenance costs
Strong modding potential and community support
Good winter daily driver capability
Design has grown on people over time
cons: Steering feels numb (though can be improved with mods)
Software update issues with infotainment system
Fender liner rubbing with lowered suspension and aggressive wheels
Not an investment vehicle
expertReviews.verdict: Highly recommends the G87 M2 as excellent value in 2025. Owner emphasizes it's one of the few remaining manual, RWD, high-horsepower sports cars available and urges buyers not to hesitate. Considers it a future classic that should be celebrated and enjoyed, though warns against buying as an investment.

expertReviews.title: 2025 BMW M2 (G87) Review! The Last True M Car?
pros: Powerful S58 twin-turbo 3.0L straight-6 engine with 473 hp
Available 6-speed manual transmission option
Excellent aftermarket potential with tuning capabilities up to 700hp
Impressive interior with alcantara steering wheel and quality materials
Good trunk space for a compact sports car
Customizable M driving modes and exhaust valve control
cons: Limited rear seat space
Controversial rear-end styling design
High starting price at $65,000
No 360-degree camera system
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 BMW M2 G87 appears to be a compelling enthusiast car with its powerful S58 engine, manual transmission availability, and extensive customization options. The reviewer appreciates the build quality, interior materials, and performance potential, though notes styling controversy and space limitations. Positioned as potentially 'the last true M car,' it offers strong performance credentials and tuning potential.
